<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1928-03-17T18:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1928-03-17T18:00:00-05:00" n="400" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d400">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">817.00/5471: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Minister in Nicaragua</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Eberhardt</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Extract—Paraphrase]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1928-03-17T18:00:00-05:00"><hi rend="italic">March 17,
                                        1928—6 p.m.</hi></date></dateline></opener>
                        <p>71. …</p>
                        <p>The Department perceives no objection to following the course of action
                            set forth in your telegram No. 130, March 16, 7 p.m. Our understanding
                            would be that General McCoy would be elected by the Supreme Court on the
                            nomination of the President of the United States. See the memorandum
                            attached to the letter of May 15, 1927, from President Diaz to President
                            Coolidge.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Kellogg</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>